ish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"FitzAlan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name  <i>Alan</i> (  see  Allen  ), ‘son of  <i>Alan</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]},{"name":"Allen","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Alain</i>, <i>Alein</i> (Old Breton <i>Alan</i>), from a Celtic personal name of great antiquity and obscurity. In England the personal name is now usually spelled <i>Alan</i>, the surname <i>Allen</i>; in Scotland the surname is more often <i>Allan</i>. From 1139 it was common in Scotland, where the surname also derives from Gaelic <i>Ailéne</i>, <i>Ailín</i>, from <i>ail</i> ‘rock’. The present-day frequency of the surname Allen in England and Ireland is partly accounted for by the popularity of the personal name among Breton followers of William the Conqueror, by whom it was imported first to Britain and then to Ireland. Saint Alan(us) was a 5th-century bishop of Quimper, who was a cult figure in medieval Brittany. Another Saint Al(l)an was a Cornish or Breton saint of the 6th century, to whom a church in Cornwall is dedicated.","English: occasionally perhaps from the rare Middle English femaje personal name <i>Aline</i> (Old French <i>Adaline</i>, <i>Aaline</i>), a pet form of ancient Germanic names in <i>Adal-</i>, especially <i>Adalheidis</i> (see   Allis  ).","French: variant of   Allain  , a cognate of 1 above, and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]},{"name":"Gethin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from a lenited adjectival form of the byname <i>Cethin</i> ‘dusky, swarthy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gethen","meanings":["Traditional: from a lenited adjectival form of the byname <i>Cethin</i> ‘dusky, swarthy’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":52,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Gethin de FitzAlan was born in 1403, in Beguildy, Radnorshire, Wales as the daughter of FitzAlan ap Dafydd and Tangwystl Llwyd verch Gruffudd. She had at least 1 daughter with John Vaughan. She died in Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"1403–1474":"1403–1474","1405–1457":"1405–1457","1442–1531":"1442–1531","–1403":"–1403","1403":"1403","after 1403":"pärast 1403","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1531":"1531","1442":"1442","1474":"1474","1405":"1405","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Coln St Aldwyn, Gloucestershire, England":"Coln St Aldwyn's, Gloucestershire, England","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","Beguildy, Radnorshire, Wales":"Beguildy, Radnorshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1403–1474":"1403–1474","1405–1457":"1405–1457","1442–1531":"1442–1531","–1403":"–1403","1403":"1403","after 1403":"1403 jälkeen","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1531":"1531","1442":"1442","1474":"1474","1405":"1405","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Coln St Aldwyn, Gloucestershire, England":"Coln St Aldwyn's, Gloucestershire, England","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","Beguildy, Radnorshire, Wales":"Beguildy, Radnorshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1403–1474":"1403–1474","1405–1457":"1405–1457","1442–1531":"1442–1531","–1403":"–1403","1403":"1403","after 1403":"après 1403","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1531":"1531","1442":"1442","1474":"1474","1405":"1405","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Coln St Aldwyn, Gloucestershire, England":"Coln St Aldwyn's, Glouce